deck_excerpt: THE 8 TIME YCS WINNING STRATEGY - SNAKE EYES!
deck_description:
Don't mind me, just posting my personal try hard Locals Snake-Eye decklist! Snake-Eyes has won the last 8 YCS, and a lot of duelists are absolutely bored and burnt out (pun intended lol) of this fire-centric meta that Ms. Diabellestarr has been dominating. Can't wait until this stale tier 1 deck is finally phased out for something new! Until then... It's good to learn what the best deck of the format does.

The Snake-Eyes engine is straightforward enough - everybody and their mom knows what the cards do and what the optimal combos are by this point. The staples are included specifically to hardcounter the handtrap heavy meta of the current TCG format - hence the Crossout Desginators along with it's banish targets. The sidedeck is full of cards that metagame certain strategies.

If you want a detailed guide on how to play this deck, check out my earlier article by clicking here.

If you have any questions about this deck, feel free to ask me in the comments below!

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

Lunchbox Drafting

Designed for 2 Players.

Based on the idea of a lunchbox with 6 copies of each card in it. An IRL Lunchbox would have 360 cards.

Generally Lunchboxes have a clear 2 Player theme ie Spellcasters vs Fiends, Amazonness vs Harpie, Warrior Zombie Onslaught, etc. 

Players quickly assembled their decks from the pre-built lunchbox card pool before dueling. 

60 Cards

18 Effect Monsters

12 Normal Monsters

18 Spells

14 Traps

Extra deck monsters are not included in the 60 card total.

Some lunchbox drafts use a single field spell for theming, in this case the duel starts with the field spell active.

deck_excerpt: Turbo out Chaos Archfiend and swing for game!
deck_description:
This is an Archfiend build that uses a small Fiendsmith package to boost its consistency, and uses the likes of Weiss, Lightsworn Archfiend and Archfiend Palabyrinth to summon Chaos Archfiend.

Example combos:

Bone Archfiend + Heiress/Palabyrinth = Chaos Archfiend (Bone send Vision, Vision search Crimson, Crimson add Vision, summon Vision, link into Muckraker, revive Bone, send Heiress, search Palabyrinth, Palabyrinth target Muckraker, summon Weiss, synchro)

As does Tour Guide + Heiress/Palabyrinth (same as above but Rhino Warrior off Tour Guide to send Bone to revive off Muckraker)

Bone Archfiend + Fiendsmith also = Chaos Archfiend because you can dump Weiss and then revive it off Lacrimosa

Bone by itself = Soul of Rage (Bone send Vision, Vision search Crimson, Crimson add Vision, summon Vision, link into Yama, search Aruha, pop Crimson, link into Rage)

I'll come back and edit this to include a more comprehensive breakdown, but for now feel free to copy the deck and have a play. Example games all in the video.

deck_excerpt: Cyberse has an abundance of ways to gain advantage and draw cards

Just a deck I cooked using dracob's guide "BASED P.U.N.K v1" use that if you want to build your own

The links besides Hieratic Seal I only used in 1 game, but all of it was needed: Striker Dragon to make an S.P. that banishes (a Kashtira Birth), then into Promethean into Amblowhale to out my opponent's Kashtira Tri-Heart

Dharc, Kubelt, and Blackrose Moonlight Dragon never came up.

Only a single opponent actually asked to see my Trident Dragion; all others just conceded when I started making my attacking plays in the Battle Phase.

Droll came in clutch against a Chimera Melodius deck

In the side there was no need for Dimension Shifter or Heat Wave. I opted to keep it more safe. Rivalry way too strong to ignore, though.

The Kashtira Fenrir package was great for a threatening board presense, and also a great turn 1 summon in case I'm made to go first.

Koa'ki Meiru Drago I rarely sided in, and it never came up.

deck_description: ygoprodeck.com

Dark World Yubel Control Deck

This deck focuses on utilizing the "Dark World" archetype to control the flow of the duel and summon powerful monsters like Yubel and Grapha. Here's a breakdown of its core strategies:

  • Yubel Powerhouse: The deck utilizes multiple forms of Yubel, including "Yubel - Terror Incarnate" for swarming and "Yubel - The Ultimate Nightmare" for powerful removal. "Spirit of Yubel" provides additional resources and graveyard manipulation.
  • Dark World Engine: "Reign-Beaux," "Grapha," "Sillva," and "Snoww" form the core of the Dark World engine, searching each other and generating advantage.
  • Discard Fodder and Advantage: Cards like "Genta," "Broww," and "Gruesome Grave Squirmer" provide discard fodder for Dark World effects while offering benefits like searching or graveyard setup. "Trade-In" and "Card Destruction" further fuel the discard strategy, while "Samsara D Lotus" and "Nightmare Pain" reward you for discarding.
  • Search and Consistency: "Dark World Accession," "Dark World Archives," and "The Gates of Dark World" search for key Dark World cards, ensuring you have the tools you need.
  • Control Elements: "Skill Drain" shuts down your opponent's monster effects, while "Eternal Favorite" protects your Yubel monsters. "Nightmare Throne" offers additional field control with its effect negation.
  • Extra Deck Toolbox: The Extra Deck offers a variety of options depending on the situation. "Yubel - The Loving Defender Forever" and "Grapha, Dragon Overlord of Dark World" capitalize on the Dark World strategy. "Number 97: Draglubion" and "The Zombie Vampire" provide removal, while "Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy" offers card advantage. The deck also features generic Rank 4 and Link monsters for various needs.

This deck prioritizes controlling the duel through targeted removal, hand disruption with Dark World effects, and strong monsters like Yubel. It utilizes its discard strategy to gain advantage and access powerful effects. Be aware that "Card Destruction" can be risky, so use it strategically.

"Exodia" é um arquétipo de monstros do Tipo Mago de TREVAS, com o primeiro membro lançado em A Lenda do Dragão Branco de Olhos Azuis e seu primeiro suporte lançado na Millennium Box Gold Edition. Ele são focados em condições de vitória alternativa. Ele está relacionado ao arquétipo "Forbidden One".

Enquanto muitas pessoas se referem aos cards "Forbidden One" como cards "Exodia", apenas "Exodia the Forbidden One" (a cabeça) é parte deste arquétipo.

O card principal, "Exodia the Forbidden One", é um dos cinco primeiros Monstros de Efeito a serem lançados e o primeiro card a ter uma condição de vitória alternativa.

Notavelmente, "Exodia the Forbidden One" e os outros cards "Forbidden One" foram os únicos monstros já mencionados especificamente no manual de regras (exceto como um exemplo), devido à "Exodia the Forbidden One" ser o único card com uma condição de vitória alternativa naquele momento.

deck_description:
Category: Tournament Meta Decks (TCG)

Tournament Meta Decks are current-level Meta Decks that are capable of going up against the best of the best. These are curated lists that cannot be uploaded by regular users.

Creator: Thomas Jendros

Tournament: Belgium National Championship 2024 – June 8th 2024

Placement: Top 8

Tried out the new ice barrier support in EDOPro and I ended up liking it a lot! Here's the list I cooked up after testing for a bit. The main goal is to summon Lancea and hopefully another synchro 10 to protect the field (I preferred Gymir Aegerine). Revealer is your ideal starter - the mirror mage is mostly used with discard/foolish burial, and Georgius is your way to bring out Wayne for Frozen Domain, although his other searches aren't bad in case you drew it. Once Lancea is on the field, your targets for it are Raiho and Defender. I usually search Raiho first to force the opponent to go minus, and defender second to deny combat. 

Generic interruptions can be swapped out as desired. I personally have phantazmay in the side deck for Snake-eye or any other link matchups, ghost ogre to deal with Tenpai, dark ruler + evenly for going second, and synchro zone for going first.

 

I didn't do any specific ratio testing - I have a hunch that mirror magic master could be playable at 1 copy. Water charmer could potentially be swapped out for Almiraj to get mirror master into the grave (though I never bricked on him in testing). Little Knight probably has its use but I did not include her to save my wallet. In cases where you're playing Little Knight, be wary of waterlocking yourself.

deck_description:
I think that Fiendsmith as an archetype is pretty cool. I know that currently, some people aren’t seeing it more than a 1-card combo without using your Normal Summon that gets you a D/D/D Wave High King Caesar onto your field for 2 Solemn Warning effects. But to me, while I still think that is very powerful, it either just serves to protect you against Nibiru or it just adds on 2 more interruptions on a board that already had enough interaction to run your opponent out of resources without the inclusion of Caesar. Fiendsmith has 1 Level 9 monster in Fiendsmith Dies Irae who is a Level 9 LIGHT Fiend Fusion Monster that requires The Fiendsmith and 2 LIGHT Fiends as Fusion Material. It can Quick Effect negate the effects of face-up cards on the field until the end of the turn up to the total Link Rating of the Link Monsters equipped to it and if it is sent to the GY, you can shuffle 1 other LIGHT Fiend from your GY into the Deck or Extra Deck to target and send a card on the field to the GY. Putting together Fiendsmith and Prediction Princess seemed incredibly weird to me even though I’ve created worse variants like Code Talker Prediction Princess. On one hand, you could just play the Fiendsmith engine to get to Dies Irae and have no other usage for the engine outside of that. On the other hand, you could actually play Fiendsmith Prediction Princess, using the Fiendsmith cards for more than just getting to a Level 9. And to be fair, there is a lot that I want to do with Fiendsmith because Prediction Princess gives you access to cards like Mereologic Aggregator and Sacred Tree Beast Hyperyton who have some unique interactions with the Fiendsmith Fusion and Link Monsters. And I think that I have managed to make that work with this Decklist here. So, for our combo, we need The Fiendsmith, World Legacy Monstrosity, and any way to get another monster onto our field like a Normal Summon or a free Summon. Let’s say that will be us Normal Summoning Ash Blossom. We are going through a similar combo that you may have already seen people using to go from 1 The Fiendsmith into Wave High King Caesar, but we are going to be tweaking it at the end to transition us into Dies Irae instead. Activate The Fiendsmith to discard itself to search Fiendsmith Sanctus. Activate Fiendsmith Sanctus to Summon a Fiendsmith Token. Link that Token into Fiendsmith Requiem. Requiem Tributes itself to Special Summon another The Fiendsmith from Deck. Activate your other The Fiendsmith in GY to shuffle Fiendsmith Requiem from GY into Extra Deck to Special Summon itself from GY. Link your 2 The Fiendsmiths into Moon of the Closed Sky. Normal Summon Ash Blossom and then Link Ash and Moon of the Closed Sky into Fiendsmith Sequentia. Sequentia activates its effect to shuffle both The Fiendsmiths and Moon of the Closed Sky into Deck/Extra Deck to Fusion Summon Fiendsmith Dies Irae. Activate Monstrosity targeting Dies Irae to Special Summon Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and Deus-X Krawler from Deck. Xyz Deus-X and Dies Irae into Mereologic Aggregator to send Herald of the Arc Light from Extra Deck. And it is the same song and dance from there on. While it was weird to me at first, looking at it now, Fiendsmith is not too bad with Prediction Princess. On one hand, if you do draw Monstrosity, you are able to go through the Aggregator line to get your Ritual components. On the other, because the Fiendsmith engine is pretty small for all things considered and because it doesn’t require a Normal Summon, you can play Diviner of the Herald to get more Ritual searches from sending Herald of the Arc Light while also playing a decent amount of non-engine. You could also decide to play things like Pre-Preparation of Rites and Prediction Ritual to have more access to your Ritual stuff if you value that over more non-engine. And of course, don’t forget that you can still do Fiendsmith plays to get to Wave High King Caesar to either protect yourself against Nibiru or to use as interruption when you draw the stuff you need for your Prediction Princess plays already. This Deck doesn’t show off the potential of Fiendsmith Prediction Princess as much as it displays the power of Fiendsmith as a 1-card combo enabler. While I still think that Fiendsmith Prediction Princess is good, it just requires you to make the decision between playing more engine or more non-engine to either see more of your Prediction Princess cards or to have more options for interruption, especially for going second. 

For the monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei is a Quick Effect to flip a monster face-up or face-down and during the End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down. Tarotreith can either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. On flip, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters either face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from GY face-down if she was tributed and sent there. On flip, she can add a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand, and while she’s face-up on field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. For our Flips, we have 1 Deus-X Krawler and 1 Pot of the Forbidden. Deus-X negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it from Deck. Pot of the Forbidden, on flip, allows you to draw 2 cards, return all Spell/Trap Cards on field to the hand, destroy all monsters your opponent controls, or look at your opponent’s hand and shuffle a card of your choice back into the Deck. 1 Trias Hierarchia which can be sent off of Diviner of the Herald and Summon itself back from GY by Tributing said Diviner. This card is more or less just a Level 9 monster you can access off of Diviner that you can target with Monstrosity to get Deus-X and Pot of the Forbidden from the Deck in a situation where you have Diviner but you don’t have The Fiendsmith. 3 The Fiendsmith. You can discard it to add a Fiendsmith Spell/Trap from your Deck to your hand, while it is on field, you can target a Fiendsmith equip card and a monster on the fiend and send both to the GY, and if it is in the Gy, you can shuffle 1 other LIGHT Fiend monster from your Gy into the Deck/Extra Deck to Special Summon this card. As you would pretty much already know, this card by itself is a 1-card Rank 6 Xyz Monster or it can allow you to go into a Fiendsmith Fusion Monster if you go for Fiendsmith Sequentia. 3 Diviner of the Herald. Because you don’t have a Normal Summon in the Fiendsmith engine, we can play this card to either get a Level 9 on field in Trias Hierarchia or you can use it as your Normal Summonable monster which would then be used for Link Material during your Fiendsmith combo who can also get you a Ritual Spell or Ritual Monster by sending Herald of the Arc Light to GY on Summon. And for the rest of the monsters, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and 3 Effect Veiler. Again, you could cut any number of these to play more engine pieces in Pre-Preparation of Rites and Prediction Ritual. 

Spell/Traps: 1 Fiendsmith Sanctus and 3 Fiendsmith Tractus. Tractus Special Summons a Fiendsmith Token (Fiend/LIGHT/Level 1/ATK 0/DEF 0) if you control no face-up monsters or if all monsters you control are LIGHT Fiend monsters while also locking you into attacking with Fiends for the rest of the turn. Tractus is the card that you always want to search off of The Fiendsmith. The Token it Summons allows you to Link it off into Fiendsmith Requiem who then Tributes itself to get another The Fiendsmith from Deck onto Field while also putting itself into the GY for your other The Fiendsmith in GY to shuffle back to Special Summon itself, putting 2 Level 6’s onto the field. Even so, this card is not a brick that you want to keep in your Deck at all times. If you draw it, it is completely fine as you can just grab Tractus from Deck with The Fiendsmith. But you just need the 1. Its GY effect is not really relevant as I don’t see us meeting the activation requirements for Sanctus past the start of your Turn 1. Tractus searches a LIGHT Fiend and then makes you discard a card. And you can also banish it from GY to Fusion Summon a Fiendsmith Fusion using monsters from your field. Other than being an incredible card for Fabled, this basically just is 3 more copies of The Fiendsmith which is great. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. And finally, 1 Called By the Grave and 3 Infinite Impermanence. 

Extra Deck: 2 Fiendsmith Dies Irae. 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from hand or Deck on Fusion Summon. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches for a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell if sent to the GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. On Xyz Summon, it can send a monster from your Extra Deck to the GY and you can target any number of monsters in your GY up to the number of Xyz Materials it has, detach the same number of Xyz Materials, and attach the targets in GY to it as material. Something to note about Aggregator’s first effect is that it can trigger the GY effects of the Fiendsmith Fusion Monsters as they have an effect that activates when sent to GY. Dies Irae shuffles another LIGHT Fiend in GY into Deck/Extra Deck and targets and sends a card on the field to the GY. Fiendsmith Lacrimosa shuffles 1 other LIGHT Fiend in GY into Deck/Extra Deck to inflict 1200 damage to your opponent. It can also send a Fiendsmith Link to allow it to equip itself from GY to a Fiendsmith monster you control, but that is less value than what you can accomplish with Essentially, on a following turn, you can go for another Aggregator to send Dies Irae from Extra Deck to GY and then have the ability to target and send a card on field to GY. But this also works when Aggregator reattaches Dies Irae from GY and is sent to GY as well. The same goes for Sacred Tree Beast Hyperyton’s negation effect, but we aren’t playing it for the sake of space. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. Laevateinn tributing itself also sends a Dies Irae it has as material to GY which can also be used to trigger its effect. 1 D/D/D Wave High King Caesar which when a Spell/Trap Card or monster effect is activated that includes an effect that Special Summons a monster, you can detach a material to negate the activation and destroy that card with this effect not being once per turn. I have played with this card in Sharks alongside Xyz Revive Splash in the past, but with the Fiendsmith cards, summoning it in any Deck is a breeze. 1 S:P Little Knight. 1 Moon of the Closed Sky. This is not necessary as you could just play the second copy of Sequentia instead since we just need a second Link-2 Light Fiend in our Extra Deck. Speaking of, 1 Fiendsmith Sequentia which requires 2 monsters including a LIGHT Fiend as material and during your Mani Phase, you can Fusion Summon a Fiend monster from your Extra Deck by shuffling the materials from your GY into the Deck. Its other effect is not necessary in this Deck. Finally, 1 Fiendsmith Requiem which is a Link-1 that requires a LIGHT Fiend as material and you can Quick Effect tribute it during the Main Phase to Special Summon a Fiendsmith monster from hand or Deck.

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 2 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag, 1 Droll & Lock Bird, 3 Crossout Designator, 3 Dark Ruler No More, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: Insert Bad to the Bone riff
deck_description:
I think that Memento is a really cool Deck. It definitely was rough coming out of Valiant Smashers (at least not as bad as Vaalmonica), but with the support it is has gotten from Phantom Nightmare in Mementotlan Ghattic, from Legacy of Destruction in Mementotlan Twin Dragon, and soon in Infinite Forbidden in Mementomictlan Tecuhtlica - Combined Conqueror, Mementotlan Mystical Sheep, and Mementotlan Fusion, the Deck is now very playable with several 1-card combos that end you on some of the Deck’s more unique plays. And it just so happens that Mementomictlan Tecuhtlica - Combined Conqueror is a Level 9 monster. It is a Level 9 EARTH Illusion Fusion Monster that requires 3 Memento monsters as Fusion Material. On Fusion Summon, it allows you to send 3 Memento cards from your Deck and/or Extra Deck to the GY and you can Quick Effect target an equal number of Memento monsters you control and cards your opponent controls to destroy them. And while this card is in your GY, you can banish it to add a Mementomictlan from your Deck to your hand. This card, even though it requires 3 Memento monsters, is actually pretty easy to Summon due to Memento Mystical Sheep and Mementotlan Fusion. Being able to send 3 Memento cards on Summon is actually a very powerful effect considering that you can send cards like Mementotlan Fusion or even another copy of Combined Conqueror to either search for another Memento Spell/Trap or search for Mementomictlan. But it can also be used to get enough Memento names into the GY to Summon Mementoal Tecuhtlica - Combined Creation or to put a Memento Trap into GY to set it during the End Phase with Mementomictlan. Combined Conqueror is also interruption itself which gives it even more purpose. However, because we are combining Memento with Prediction Princess, we run into a couple issues. Memento doesn’t play too well with cards outside of its own archetype. It definitely can, but you want to see Memento names more often than not, so you have to play a large number of them. They also have a lot of cards you don’t necessarily want to draw either, but not hard garnets. So, we have to make a decision between playing a large Memento package to end on Memento cards in addition to our Prediction Princess plays or play the core Memento cards we need to help us transition to Prediction Princess plays. I decided to play the core Memento cards primarily because of the redundancy of playing Memento Cranium Burst in addition to Deus-X Krawler. Why want 5 monster negates when you already have continuous monster negation with Deus-X. Even if we could use Whirlwind Weasel for an alternative Flip option to Deus-X, it is another brick that also requires us to play more unnecessary cards to set up Cranium Burst. This Deck has 2 combos you can do to get to Combined Conqueror. The first requires you to draw Mementotlan Dark Blade which allows us to set up a Combined Creation to potentially bring back Combined Conqueror from GY on our opponent’s turn for at least 2 pops in addition to our Prediction Princess plays. The second requires you to start with Mementotlan Angwitch which gets us straight to Combined Conqueror, transitioning to Prediction Princess plays. It can potentially also get us to Combined Creation, but more often than not, it doesn’t put enough names into rotation. Let’s say we start with Mementotlan Dark Blade. Normal Summon it and use its effect to destroy itself to Summon Angwitch from Deck. Angwitch on Summon adds Mementotlan Tatsunootoshigo from Deck. Tatsunootoshigo activates to Summon itself from hand and then activate its other effect to pop itself to send Mementotlan Mace and another name like Dark Blade or Angwitch to GY. Angwitch’s other effect pops herself to Summon back Mace from GY. Mace uses its effect to pop itself to add Mementotlan Fusion from Deck. Activate Mementotlan Fusion which allows you to Fuse using your GY since a monster in your possession was destroyed this turn. Shuffle Tatsunootoshigo and the second copy of Angwitch or Dark Blade (whichever you sent earlier) from GY into Deck to Fusion Summon Mementotlan Twin Dragon. On Fusion Summon, Twin Dragon pops itself to add Mementotlan Mystical Sheep and another name which can be Combined Creation or another Memento monster from Deck to hand, let’s say you added Combined Creation. Twin Dragon activates in GY as it was destroyed to Summon back any Level 6 or lower Memento name in GY. Activate Mystical Sheep in hand to Special Summon itself since a monster in your possession was destroyed by card effect this turn. On Summon, it Fusion Summons a Memento Fusion Monster using materials from hand or field. Fuse itself, the Memento monster you summoned from GY off of Twin Dragon, and the Combined Creation in your hand into Combined Conqueror into your EMZ. Conqueror activates to send any 3 Memento cards from Deck/Extra Deck to GY (it does not matter). Now, if you have World Legacy Monstrosity in hand, you can target Combined Conqueror with it to get Trias Hierarchia and Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag from Deck and then overlay for Mereologic Aggregator to transition to full Prediction Princess combo. Later, you can shuffle 5 Memento names excluding Combined Conqueror into Deck to Special Summon Combined Creation from GY. You can either use it as Link Material with Aggregator for I:P Masquerena or S:P Little Knight or you can keep it on field to bring back Conqueror during your opponent’s turn for potentially 2 pops. If we started with Angwitch, Normal Summon her, use her to search for Tatsunootoshigo. Tatsunootoshigo Summons itself from hand, popping itself to send Mace and another name from Deck to GY. Angwitch pops herself to Summon back Mace. Mace pops itself to search for Mementotlan Fusion. Mementotlan Fusion shuffles 3 Mementos from GY into Deck to Summon Combined Conqueror. Conqueror can send anything (it does not matter). Then, if you have Monstrosity or Kaku in hand, you can transition to Prediction Princess plays. Overall, I would say that Memento Prediction Princess is neat, but it is not that optimal. Memento having a lot of 1-card combos is really nice, but with Combined Conqueror being EARTH Attribute, it is not the most optimal Level 9 to be using for Prediction Princess. I would much rather play pure Memento. 

For the monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei is a Quick Effect to flip a monster face-up or face-down and during the End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down. Tarotreith can either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. On flip, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters either face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from GY face-down if she was tributed and sent there. On flip, she can add a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand, and while she’s face-up on field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. For our Flips, we have 1 Deus-X Krawler and 1 Pot of the Forbidden. Deus-X negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it from Deck. Pot of the Forbidden, on flip, allows you to draw 2 cards, return all Spell/Trap Cards on field to the hand, destroy all monsters your opponent controls, or look at your opponent’s hand and shuffle a card of your choice back into the Deck. 1 Trias Hierarchia which goes along with our 3 Diviner of the Herald. It might seem strange to see Diviner being played when we already have other monsters that facilitate an entire combo themselves on Normal Summon like Angwitch and Dark Blade, but Diviner is in this Deck because if you draw Diviner and a Memento name other than Mace, you have full Prediction Princess combo as well. Mementotlan Mace is a Level 1 Fairy monster which means that it can be Summoned off of Diviner after it has been Tributed off of Trias Hierarchia. Mace then destroys itself to search for Mementotlan Fusion which Fusion Summons using Mace in GY and the other Memento name in hand for Twin Dragon who pops itself on Fusion Summon to search for Mystical Sheep and another Memento name. Twin Dragon triggers on destruction to bring back the other Memento name in GY and Mystical Sheep activates to Special Summon itself from hand. Sheep and the two other Memento names on field and in hand Fuse with Sheep’s effect for Combined Conqueror where it and Trias Hierarchia are 2 Level 9’s you can Xyz into Aggregator. Hierarchia also serves as a Level 9 to Summon from Deck when targeting Combined Conqueror on field with Monstrosity. 2 Gizmek Kaku, the Supreme Shining Sky Stag. This card can activate to Special Summon itself from hand if there is a monster in the EMZ. You can just Special Summon Combined Conqueror into the EMZ and Summon Kaku from hand for 2 Level 9’s on field, and Kaku also serves as a Level 9 to Summon from Deck off of Monstrosity targeting Conqueror. 1 Memento Tecuhtlica - Combined Creation which Must be Special Summoned from hand/GY by shuffling 5 other Memento monsters with different names from hand/GY into the Deck/Extra Deck. And once per turn if your opponent activates a card or effect, you can Special Summon 1 Memento monster from hand or GY. You really do not need to play this card. But it gives you another form of interruption given that you start with Mementotlan Dark Blade as it can Summon back Combined Conqueror if your opponent activates a card or effect. In place of this, you could play the second copy of Mace. 1 Mementotlan Tatsunootoshigo which can Special Summon itself from hand if you do not control any face-up monsters other than Memento monsters. Its other effect allows you to destroy a Memento monster you control for effect and send any number of Memento monsters with different names from your Deck to the GY whose total Levels are less than or equal to the destroyed monster’s original Level. 3 Mementotlan Dark Blade and 3 Mementotlan Angwitch. Dark Blade and discard a Memento card on Summon to target and destroy a Spell/Trap your opponent controls and it can also destroy a memento monster you control for effect to Special Summon a Level 3 or lower Memento monster from Deck. You could use this card as Spell/Trap removal, but it is primarily here to get Angwitch from Deck. Angwitch can add another Memento monster from Deck to hand on Summon and you can target a Level 2 or lower Memento monster in your GY and destroy a Memento monster you control for effect to Summon back the targeted monster. 1 Mementotlan Mystical Sheep which only has 2 relevant effects we are using. If a monster(s) in your possession was destroyed by card effect this turn, you can Special Summon it from your hand. And on Summon, it can Fusion Summon a Memento Fusion Monster from your Extra Deck using material from hand or field. This card is nuts in a pure Memento Deck, but here, it is just a way for us to transition from Twin Dragon to Combined Conqueror. 1 Mementotlan Mace which we are only using to pop a Memento monster we control for effect to add a Memento card from Deck to hand. Again, you can decide not to play Combined Creation to play a second Mace if you want. 

For Spell/Traps: 3 Pot of Prosperity. 2 Mementotlan Fusion which can Fusion Summon any Fusion Monster from Extra Deck using monsters from your hand or field as material including a Memento and if a monster(s) in your possession was destroyed this turn, you can also shuffle Memento monsters from GY into the Deck as material. Also, you can banish it from your GY and destroy a monster you control to add a Memento Spell/Trap from your Deck to your hand. This card being able to get out any Fusion Monster is incredible as it gives you the ability to go for Guardian Chimera on your opponent’s turn if you want as it is a Quick-Play Spell Card, and being able to use your hand, field, and GY for material is such a huge boon this card gives to Memento. Furthermore, its effect to search a Memento Spell/Trap can also search another copy of it which means that you can really set-up for a potential Guardian Chimera on your opponent’s turn given that you do your standard combo. 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. And finally, 1 Called By the Grave and 3 Triple Tactics Talent. 

Extra Deck: 1 Trishula, the Dragon of Icy Imprisonment. 1 Guardian Chimera. 2 Mementomictlan Tecuhtlica - Combined Conqueror. 1 Memento Twin Dragon which requires 2 Memento monsters as material and on Fusion Summon, it can pop a Memento monster you control or in hand for effect to search for up to 2 Memento monsters with different names from your Deck, and if it is popped, you can Special Summon a Level 6 or lower Memento monster from your GY. 1 Master of Ham which Special Summons a Flip Monster from hand or Deck on Fusion Summon. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which searches for a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell if sent to the GY. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Gravity Controller.

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 2 Lightning Storm, the third Triple Tactics Talent, 3 Infinite Impermanence, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: SPRIGHT JET BACK TO 2 IN MASTERDUEL!
deck_description:
Even after a year later, Spright Runick remains as powerful and effective as ever vs. the Masterduel meta!

With the recent bump of Spright Jet from 1 to 2 due to the recent banlist, Spright Runick is as unstoppable as ever! The ridiculously strong combination of Spright and Runick's smothering control and endless grind game create a deck that all strategies would have to fear and respect. Sprights ending on 3-5 interruptions (Red's monster negate, Carrot's S/T negate, Smasher's banish, and I:P Masquerena's quick link) combined with Runick's draw 3 and quick play spells generally stop any deck cold in their tracks. Both archetypes combined have a potential 10+ interruptions for your opponent to slog through, while maintaining a superior resource loop - outpacing most other strategies!

If you want a detailed guide on how to pilot this deck, check out my article from a couple last year.

Want to see the deck in action? Scroll to the very bottom for the Youtube video!

deck_description:
Dark World Control Deck with Union Engine

This deck focuses on controlling the duel through monster negation and hand disruption while utilizing the "Dark World" archetype's synergy to swarm the field and advantage generation.

Monsters (29):

  • Dark World Engine (18):
    • Reign-Beaux, Overking of Dark World, Grapha, Dragon Lord of Dark World, Sillva, Warlord of Dark World, Snoww, Unlight of Dark World, Genta, Gateman of Dark World, and Broww, Huntsman of Dark World form the core of the strategy. They discard themselves to fuel Dark World effects and provide search or advantage.
    • Ceruli, Guru of Dark World offers situational hand disruption.
  • Union Engine (6):
    • A-Assault Core, B-Buster Drake, Y-Dragon Yearhead, and Z-Zillion Tank are Union monsters that combine with Union Driver for strong effects and removal.
    • Union Hangar helps search for Union monsters and Union Activation facilitates their special summoning.
  • Hand Traps & Staples (5):
    • Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring and Infinite Impermanence offer powerful hand negation to disrupt your opponent's plays.
    • Called by the Grave provides graveyard recursion for banished cards or counters opponent's graveyard effects.
  • Tech Choices (1):
    • Therion "King" Regulus is a versatile monster that can negate effects or return banished cards to the deck.

Spells (19):

  • Dark World Spells (7):
    • Dark World Dealings allows for discarding and searching, fueling the Dark World engine.
    • Dark Corridor provides graveyard recursion for Dark World monsters.
    • The Gates of Dark World sets up a continuous discard outlet for Dark World effects.
  • Union Support (3):
    • Union Activation facilitates Union monster summoning.
    • Terraforming searches for The Gates of Dark World.
  • Search & Utility (5):
    • Foolish Burial sends monsters to the graveyard for setup.
    • Unauthorized Reactivation can bring back banished Union monsters or Spells/Traps.
    • Dark World Accession and Dark World Archives offer situational searching based on the game state.
  • Staples (4):
    • Called by the Grave provides graveyard recursion or counters graveyard effects.

Traps (3):

  • Disruption (2):
    • Therion Discolosseum disrupts the opponent's special summoning.

Extra Deck (15):

  • Dark World Fusions (2):
    • Grapha, Dragon Overlord of Dark World is the deck's boss monster with negation and destruction effects.
  • Union Fusions (2):
    • ABC-Dragon Buster provides removal and piercing damage.
  • Rank 4 Xyz (4):
    • Knightmare Unicorn offers monster negation, while S:P Little Knight searches for Union monsters.
    • Utility options include Accesscode Talker for OTKs and Platinum Gadget for Rank 8 plays.
  • Generic Links & Rank 8 (4):
    • Saryuja Skull Dread provides card advantage, while Coach King Giantrainer offers protection.
    • Number 38: Hope Harbinger Dragon Titanic Galaxy and Number 60: Dugares the Timeless are situational Rank 8 options.
  • Underworld Goddess of the Closed World (1):
    • A tech option for graveyard recursion and banishing.

Overall Strategy:

  • Utilize Dark World monsters to discard for advantage and set up the graveyard.
  • Use Union monsters with Union Driver for removal and field presence.
  • Disrupt your opponent's plays with hand traps and Therion Discolosseum.
  • Aim to end the game with Grapha, Dragon Overlord of Dark World or strong Union Fusions.

This deck offers a balance between control elements and aggressive plays with the Union engine. It's versatile and can adapt to different situations.

Creator: Guilherme Souza Ribeiro

deck_name: My bestie and your bestie sitting round the fire my bestie and y
deck_excerpt: Lotus Springans FTK (with the cards I have and the lyrics of a song, that is stuck in my head)
deck_description:
The idea is, that one of 9 of the Springans Monster + one of 9 of the cards, that are Great Sand Sea - Gold Golgonda lead to a Primathmech Alembertian, which searches Summoner Monk without having used the Normal Summon. Which then leads to the setup of the Lotus FTK. 

Why did I play it? I had a dream of playing it and heard the song as well. 

With 1 Springans Monster + 1 Field Spell (searcher):

     0. Search Field Spell

  1. Activate Great Sand Sea - Gold Golgonda 
  2. Use the Field Spell to summon Springans Merrymaker 
  3. Send a different Springans Monster to the GY with Merrymaker
  4. Attach both Springans Monsters in the GY to Merrymaker
  5. Overlay to Gigantic "Champion" Sargas 
  6. Search Tally-ho! Springans with Sargas
  7. Use Tally-ho, detach all Materials from Sargas, search the last Springans Monster and summon all 3 Springans Monsters
  8. Bounce the Field Spell back to the hand
  9. Overlay the 3 Springans Monsters into Primathmech Alembertian and search Summoner Monk

From there you have 2 bodies on board, 1 Normal Summon still unused, 1 Monk in hand and at least 1 Spell in hand for Monk. That is enough for the Lotus FTK part, if you don't get interrupted.

Other Notes:

  • With 1 Springans + Small World  you can use Therion "King" Regulus as the bridge for Monk
  • Going through the Springans Combo with Monk + a Spell already in hand can bait out an Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring, which can be revived with Hiita the Fire Charmer, Ablaze as additional material.
  • Yes, Maxx "C" and Nibiru, the Primal Being are big problems.
  • Setting the Card Position Option to Auto in the End Phase, will summon Samsara Lotus to the left of Trickstar Black Catbat. So only one Double Click is needed each time the question of summoning Lotus comes up.

A lot of the decks you will play against can easily summon monsters with 3k+ atk. Inferno Tempest is a wonderful addition to this deck because once it goes off, your opponent will not be able to do much of anything unless they have ample monsters in hand or field.

The Extra Deck is full of cheap cards because you don't use it outside of Pot of Extravegance.

The Side Deck is setup to allow you to play multiple variations of this burn style so have fun!
A Simple Build, made for Budget Fun Casual play.

deck_excerpt: Yes I know this is a crime against Suship, didn't ask
deck_description:
Reasons Suship works with Snake-Eyes:

- Gunkan is fire and has extra room (and is great discard fodder lol)

- Snek is actually good

- That's it

Reasons im not playing certain cards:

- apo (cringe)

- 3x ash (gonna get hit)

- 3x wanted (gonna get hit)

- divine temple (kinda not very great when mixing 2 engines 2gether + I know u don't care about how nib-proof ur deck is)

- Makes it look like u can fit in more non-engine and teks then you otherwise could in a real deck (kinda like Evergrande)

Suggestions:

- Replace ty-phon and dharc with lyrilusc + downerd which turns this into a cool zeus deck (and saves on ty-phon)

- U can replace S:P with knightmare phoenix if ur broke (me) which also lets u use the zealantis combo w/o a monster on ur opponents field (look it up I don't wanna explain it)

- replace bonfire with 2x small world and 1x kurikara if u can't afford it

Thunks :)

Deck is very strong going first with a lot of good going second options in the main and side. Effect veiler over imperm because imperm is a dead draw off of butterfly lady. Going first side in droll or dimensional barrier over evenly matched. Going second side in dark ruler or spell removal over extender cards like armored lizard and vesiculo. Shifter is the nucular option into snake-eyes and hopefully being able to play through it.

Placement: 1st Place

It has been a long time coming, but here is the Generaider Prediction Princess Decklist. Before I get into it, I just want to say that I will be crossing off a large number of Level 9 monsters off of the list of Level 9 monsters in the game because they are just either unplayable or their associated archetype, type, or attribute just cannot work well or even function in a Prediction Princess Deck. First off is Apoqliphort Skybase which might be very obvious since it is a 3-Tribute monster that needs 3 Qli Tributes to Tribute Summon itself and it is an EARTH Attribute which means you can’t get Biblomuse out of the Deck if you target it with World Legacy Monstrosity. If Isolde, Two Tales of the Noble Knights was still unbanned, then I could see it being somewhat possible, but she’s gone and so is Skybase. Next is Infernal Flame Emperor. A monster that cannot be Special Summoned and needs 2 Tributes to Tribute Summon is really bad, especially since its effect does literally nothing. B.E.S. Blaster Cannon Core. Here’s the deal with B.E.S.: Their cards are so bad. Like they are so Battle Phase-orientated (not like that means much), and their cards are so unsynergistic and it is not like it promotes play with outside card archetypes either. Then, we have the Level 9 Red-Eyes monsters: Red-Eyes Darkness Dragon, Archfiend Black Skull Dragon and Black Skull Dragon. Dear lord, these cards are bad (not Archfiend Black Skull - it’s fine for the most part). Red-Eyes Darkness Dragon must be Special Summoned from hand by Tributing a Red-Eyes Black Dragon you control. That means that you need to get vanilla Red-Eyes onto field, have Darkness Dragon in hand, and draw Monstrosity. That is a lot to ask for. Archfiend Black Skull and Black Skull Dragon are both Fusion Monsters where Archfiend Black Skull requires a Level 7 Red-Eyes Normal Monster and a Level 6 Archfiend Normal Monster whereas Black Skull Dragon needs vanilla Red-Eyes and Summoned Skull for Fusion Material. They basically need the same Fusion Materials which is pretty stupid for a retrain in the case of Archfiend Black Skull. Black Skull Dragon is a lost cause whereas I really tried to make Archfiend Black Skull work. I looked for a card equivalent to Dragon’s Mirror since it is not searchable and I ended up with Branded in White which is searchable through things like Aluber, the Jester of Despia and Springans Kitt. Then, I looked for a way to get the Fusion Materials into GY, and I found Chemicritter Carbo Crab which, after you Normal Summon it again since it is a Gemini monster, you can use its effect to send a Gemini monster from Deck to GY and add another Gemini monster from Deck to hand where you have Red-Eyes Geminis like Red-Eyes Black Flare Dragon and Red-Eyes Archfiend of Lightning. And remember that Geminis are treated as Normal Monsters in GY, so these can be used to fuse into Archfiend Black Skull.  But that is asking for A LOT. You need Carbo Crab, a way to extra Normal Summon it like Catalyst Field, you need a way to get the Gemini you added to hand out of your hand, Branded in White or a way to get to it that does not use your Normal Summon, and World Legacy Monstrosity for Prediction Princess purposes. That’s going in the dump. I’m not going to bombard you guys with the rest. I’ll slowly explain the rest on future Prediction Princess lists.

Generaider is a very well-known Level 9 archetype (even though Prediction Princess came first). I have put off putting a Generaider Prediction Princess list out for a while because it is incredibly easy to make a Generaider Prediction Princess list and find combos that work. Loptr, Shadow of the Generaider Bosses is a Lonefire Blossom for the Deck which means you can Normal Loptr, Tribute it to Special Summon Mardel, Generaider Boss of Light from Deck, Mardel triggers on Summon to search for Generaider Boss Stage, and now just activate Boss Stage and activate World Legacy Monstrosity targeting Mardel for Prediction Princess Bibliomuse and another Level 9 from Deck. It’s not rocket science, it’s not D/D, it’s not that hard to imagine this Deck at all. You just need to find a way to both Loptr and Monstrosity and you are all set. Now let’s take a look at our Level 9 monsters. Generaider has 9 Level 9 monsters in their archetype: Naglfar, Generaider Boss of Fire, Harr, Generaider Boss of Storms, Vala, Seidhr of the Generaider Bosses, Frodi, Generaider Boss of Swords, Mardel, Generaider Boss of Light, Utgarda, Generaider Boss of Delusion, Nidhogg, Generaider Boss of Ice, Dovelgus, Generaider Boss of Iron, and Hela, Generaider Boss of Doom. You can only control 1 of each. Naglfar is Level 9 FIRE Beast-Warrior monster who can replace the destruction of a card(s) you control by battle or card effect by destroying a Generaider or Beast-Warrior monster you control instead. Harr is a Level 9 DARK Spellcaster monster who can force your opponent to send a monster from their hand or field to the GY if a card(s) is added from their Deck to their hand outside of the Draw Phase and he can also Tribute 2 Generaider and/or Spellcaster monsters you control to negate and destroy an activated card or effect belonging to your opponent. Vala is a Level 9 FIRE Fairy monster who can send 1 other Generaider card from hand to GY to Special Summon herself from hand or GY, banishing herself when she leaves the field. And if she is Special Summoned, she can Special Summon a Generaider monster from hand or GY except for another copy of herself. Frodi is a Level 9 WIND Warrior monster who can Quick Effect Tribute any number of Generaider and/or Warrior monsters you control and target the same number of monsters on the field and destroy them with your opponent being able to draw cards equal to the number of monsters that were destroyed on their field. Mardel is a Level 9 LIGHT Plant monster who, if Normal or Special Summoned, can add a Generaider card or a Plant monster from your Deck to your hand except for herself. Utgarda is a Level 9 LIGHT Rock monster who can Quick Effect Tribute 2 Generaider and/or Rock monsters you control to target a card on the field and banish it. Nidhogg is a Level 9 WATER Wyrm monster who can Quick Effect Tribute a Generaider or Wyrm monster you control when your opponent would Special Summon a monster(s) to negate the Summon and destroy those monsters. Dovelgus is a Level 9 EARTH Machine monster who can Quick Effect Tribute any number of Generaider and/or Machine monsters to Special Summon the same number of Generaider and/or Machine monsters from your hand with different names from each other and from the monsters you Tributed. Hela is a Level 9 DARK Zombie monster who can Quick Effect Tribute a Generaider or Zombie monster you control and target a Generaider or Zombie monster in your GY with a different name than the monster you Tribute and Special Summon that monster in Defense Position. I think that in a Generaider Prediction Princess Deck, all of these monsters are very playable outside of Frodi and Dovelgus. You could still very much play Frodi and Dovelgus, but their effects are just not going to be used since they are either more detrimental than good in the case of Frodi or they just don’t have that much synergy in the Deck in the case of Dovelgus. But let’s narrow down what Generaider names we should play even more. Nagalfar’s protection effect is pretty good, especially in a Prediction Princess Deck where you want to protect your Flip Monsters, especially Deus-X Krawler. But at the same time, Prediction Princess Bibliomuse already gives both targeting and destruction protection to your Ritual Monsters in addition to providing the search power for the Deck. And before anyone says that “But Nagalfar protects your whole field,” remember that we can just Summon Harr off of Boss Stage. Harr is an omni-negate and takes a card away from your opponent’s hand/field. Nagalfar replaces destruction once. Harr is an omni-negate once per turn. Same deal, but Harr can negate other cards that do not destroy as well, making it better than Nagalfar. This means that Nagalfar, while it is not bad, it isn’t the best thing you could play. Utgarda can banish a card from the field. Well, let’s take a look at its Level 9 Rock-Type brother, Pot of the Forbidden. Pot can allow you to draw 2 cards, Raigeki your opponent’s board, return all Spell/Traps on the field to the hand, or snipe a card out of your opponent’s hand. That is so much more utility than Utgarda and all you need to do is flip Pot up while you need to Tribute 2 monsters for Utgarda. Again, Utgarda is not bad, but it is just not the best thing you could be playing. Hela can being back a Generaider or Zombie from GY by Tributing a Generaider or a Zombie. With Loptr’s effect to Tribute a Generaider to Special Summon a Level 9 Generaider from Deck being a Quick Effect, Hela bringing back Loptr from GY is pretty good. But at the same time, we just do not have the board space to do this. Upon passing turn, you will usually have Tarotrei, a set Deus-X, a set Tarotreith, and a Link Monster on your field. Moving to your opponent’s turn, You already have to pick and choose what to Summon because you have Tarotreith who Special Summons a Flip Monster from Deck, Underworld Ritual in GY which can Special Summon a Bibliomuse from Deck, and then, you have Boss Stage who can get a Generaider from Deck since your opponent drew a card for turn. We have no space to really do what we want with Hela and even if you are able to get her out and use her to get back Loptr, you are just getting Harr from Deck either way. You could’ve gotten that Harr off of Boss Stage, so what is even the point? That leaves us with Harr, Vala, Mardel, and Nidhogg. These are the best Generaider Boss names you could be playing, so let’s look at the Deck. 

.For the monsters: 3 Prediction Princess Tarotrei, 1 Prediction Princess Tarotreith, and 3 Prediction Princess Bibliomuse. Tarotrei is a Quick Effect to flip a monster face-up or face-down and during the End Phase, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or GY face-down. Tarotreith can either be Ritual Summoned or Special Summoned via Tarotrei’s End Phase effect. On flip, she can Special Summon a Flip Monster from your Deck face-down and she can Quick Effect flip any number of your monsters either face-up or face-down. Bibliomuse can Special Summon herself back from GY face-down if she was tributed and sent there. On flip, she can add a Prediction Princess monster other than herself and a Ritual Spell from Deck to hand, and while she’s face-up on field, your Ritual Monsters gain targeting and destruction protection from your opponent’s effects. 1 Deus-X Krawler which negates all activated monster effects on your opponent’s side of the field after it has been flipped face-up and if it is destroyed on field, you can search for a Level 9 monster with a different Type and Attribute than it from Deck. 1 Pot of the Forbidden. On flip, it allows you to draw 2 cards, return all Spell/Trap Cards on field to the hand, destroy all monsters your opponent controls, or look at your opponent’s hand and shuffle a card of your choice back into the Deck. Starting with the first Generaider monster, 1 Nidhogg, Generaider Boss of Ice. This one can Tribute a Generaider or Wyrm monster when your opponent would Special Summon a monster(s) to negate the Summon and destroy those monsters. I am choosing to Main Deck Nidhogg over Harr because Harr needs to tribute 2 monsters for its effect whereas Nidhogg can just Tribute itself. We are still side decking Harr, but the difference between having to Tribute 2 monsters versus 1 monster is pretty substantial in this Deck because your Prediction Princess plays end you on a monster in the EMZ and at least 2 to 3 monsters in your Main Monster Zone. Then, when we get to the opponent’s turn, we have the ability to get 2 more monsters onto the field, getting us a full board of monsters. So, if we were to have Boss Stage on field and we wanted it to get out a Generaider for more interaction, I would rather start with Nidhogg because it takes less space. Getting Harr would mean that you would have to use Boss Stage’s other effect to get a Generaider Token on field as well which takes up your last remaining Monster Zone. If we know that there is a threat we need to protect ourselves against, then playing Harr would be the more optimal choice, but there is no real way to really discern that until after side decking. Next, we have 3 Vala, Sedhir of the Generaider Bosses and 3 Mardel, Generaider Boss of Light. Vala is a given as her effect is just crazy. She basically gets you to 2 Level 9’s on the field by herself. Mardel is pretty much here because of her very advantageous Type and Attribute. Her being a LIGHT Plant monster makes it so that Monstrosity can get you Bibliomuse and some other Level 9 from Deck. Vala is a Fairy, so it is not like we can use her to get to Bibliomuse. Also, she can search Boss Stage or even Loptr. Speaking of, 3 Loptr, Shadow of the Generaider Bosses. Quick Effect Lonefire for a Generadier from Deck is pretty good for all things considered. Quick side note: with the reveal of Seventh Tachyon, we can use it to reveal a Number 102: Star Seraph Sentry, a Number 103: Ragnazero, or a Number 105: Battlin’ Boxer Star Cestus in our Extra Deck to search for Loptr. I can see you doing that in Generaider, but not in this Deck. Seventh Tachyon Xyz-locks you for the rest of the turn, but in this Deck, we want to at least Link Summon once. So, don’t play it in this Deck. 3 Diviner of the Herald. With Vala existing, we don’t really need our Normal Summon, so it is nice to have a card like Diviner to potentially get us that last Ritual component we need. But Diviner can also send Vala to GY which is great as Vala can activate from hand or GY to Special Summon herself, giving Diviner a lot more utility. Lastly, 3 Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring. 

For Spell/Traps: 1 Generaider Boss Stage. If a card(s) is added from the Main Deck to your opponent’s hand, you can Special Summon 1 Generaider Monster from your Deck in Defense Position, and if you Special Summon a Generaider monster during your opponent’s turn, you can Special Summon as many Generaider Tokens (Fairy/LIGHT/Level 4/ATK 1500/DEF 1500) as possible in Attack Position, destroying them during the End Phase. Unlike in a normal Generaider Deck, we do not have the space on our field to have that many Tokens. We will mostly likely have at most 1 if we decide to go for Boss Stage, so just playing the 1 copy of it just to get an extra piece of interaction onto the field is enough. 3 Underworld Ritual of Prediction which Ritual Summons a Prediction Princess Ritual Monster from hand or GY face-up or face-down and you can banish it from GY during the Standby Phase to Special Summon a non-Ritual Prediction Princess from Deck face-down. Foolish Burial because we can send Vala as she does activate from GY and because we can send either Tarotrei or Tarotreith as we can Ritual Summon them from the GY. 3 Pot of Prosperity. 3 World Legacy Monstrosity which can either Special Summon a Level 9 monster from your hand or target a Level 9 monster you control to Special Summon 2 Level 9 monsters from your Deck with a different type and Attribute, but with different names. 1 Instant Fusion for Master of Ham. And finally, 3 Infinite Impermanence. 

Extra Deck: 1 Master of Ham which can Special Summon a Flip Monster from hand or Deck face-down on Fusion Summon. 2 Herald of the Arc Light which adds a Ritual Monster or Ritual Spell from your Deck to your hand if it is sent to the GY. 1 Divine Arsenal AA-ZEUS - Sky Thunder. 1 Super Starslayer TY-PHON - Sky Crisis. 1 Infinitrack Earth Slicer. 2 Mereologic Aggregator. 1 Laevateinn, Generaider Boss of Shadows and 1 Jormungandr, Generaider Boss of Eternity. 1 Nine-Lives Cat. 1 Underworld Goddess of the Closed World, 1 S:P Little Knight, 1 I:P Masquerena, and 1 Gravity Controller. 

Side Deck: 3 Nibiru, the Primal Being, 1 Harr, Generaider Boss of Storms, 3 Thunder King, the Lightningstrike Kaiju, 1 Kurikara Divincarnate, 2 Dark Ruler No More, 2 Lightning Storm, and 3 Evenly Matched.

deck_excerpt: Want quick easy games to grind for the WCS 2024 Qualifiers? Blind Second Sky Striker is perfect for that!
deck_description:
Raye and friends got a ton of insane power-ups with Sky Striker Camellia's generic link materials (meaning any two monsters = Camellia) and Engage Zero's field wipe! Not to mention we get an two incredible alternate arts and animations - the fiery hot Sky Striker Ace Kagari's burning retribution and the crimson red Engage of Roze!

The idea behind Blind Second Sky Strikers is to wipe out most if not all of your opponent's resources that they slap down on the board going first, and then close out the match with Sky Striker's grind game. Everyone in the 2024 WCS Qualifiers is slapping down their entire extra deck and main deck and hand into the board going first and you'll just wipe all that away with your ~20ish boardbreakers!

If you want quick easy games to grind for the WCS 2024 Qualifiers, Blind Second Sky Striker is perfect for that! If you have any questions about this deck, feel free to ask me in the comments below!

Meant to function as an introductory deck for new players.

I believe it's a mistake to recommend new players invest tons of gems into cards they don't understand, so when someone joins, why not indulge in some N/R beatdown? This is a deck that can mostly be played "on-cruve" (you're not searching for cards from deck, mostly), but still allows a bit of depth in moment-to-moment gameplay, while allowing for some surprises.

Mostly, I want this to function as a template so new players can decide what style of gameplay they prefer (add more copies of spell/traps for more of a control feel), so more experienced players can make educated recommendations, instead of just recommending players that barely understand what a tribute summon is play Salamangreat.

This is meant to be played in mirrors, so when instructing another player, you're also playing this deck.

And remember to modify as the new player gets used to their cards, or depending on what that player prefers.
Dont look at the side board if you have one brain cell

Hey! It has been a while since I have posted a deck and I would like to make a comeback with Vennominaga. You can look at previous setups by clicking here. Without further ago, let's go!

 

 

Gameplan

1) Let "Black Garden" plant at least three flowers to opposing side.

2) Use "Fusion Gate" to bring forth "Windwitch - Crystal Bell" by using Hex + Snow as materials in-hand.

3) When you have "Light Barrier" + "Diffusion Wave-Motion" + Vennominaga in your hand, assuming you have played "Into the Void" beforehand, Link Summon Saryuja. Then, activate "Light Barrier" and Special Summon Arcana with Saryuja to skip your opponent's turn by choosing the outcome as heads.

4) Set Wave-Motion to not discard due to "Into the Void" by accident and end your turn. Let Arcana send itself and Saryuja to skip your opponent's turn.

5) It's your turn now. First, activate "Wave-Motion" on Crystal Bell, which lets you attack everything in its way. Then, use Crystal Bell to copycat Vennominaga in your GY.

6) Attack these tokens generated by "Black Garden" three times with Crystal Bell, disguised as Vennominaga, to win the duel!

 

If you wonder how to save up some SR and UR points, I can show you:

- "Pot of Avarice" can be collected by purchasing "Re-Contract Universe" deck. 90 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Wonder Wand" and "Spellbook of Knowledge" can be collected by purchasing "Spellbook of Prophecy" deck. 120 SR saved and you can try a new deck!

- "Into The Void" + "Allure of Darkness" can be found within "The Infinite Void" Secret Pack to save 180 SR!

- "Pot of Acquistiveness" + "Ravenous" + "Diffusion Wave-Motion" can be found within "Legacy Pack" to save 90 SR!

- "Vennominaga" can be found within "Curse of the Serpent" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Arcana Force XXI - The World" + "Light Barrier" can be found within "Hand of Fate" Secret Pack to save 30 SR and 30 UR!

- "T.G. Hyper Librarian" can be found within "Futuristic Creatures" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

- "Black Garden" can be found within "Exquisite Jet-Black Rose" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Formula Synchron" can be found within "Stardust Ties" Secret Pack to save 60 SR!

- "Number 60: Dugares the Timeless" can be found within "Number Recall" Secret Pack to save 30 SR!

- "Moray of Avarice" can be found within "Treasures of the Cosmic Ocean" Secret Pack to save 30 UR!

 

So, in total, you can save up to 630 SR and 120 UR, if you are willing to spend some gems. Other SR and UR cards I didn't mention are essential.

 

That's all for this one. If you have any questions, feel free to ask. Have fun in Master Duel!

deck_excerpt: Redone, MUCH stronger version of my favourite deck
deck_description:
Okay, so I removed Bystials to make space for other new cards and support, so here is the whole decklist and what every card does:

MAIN:

3x Aluber, the Jester of Despia: The deck's main searcher. You're dead if it gets ashed.

3x Fallen of Albaz: The core and most important card of the whole deck.

2x Blazing Cartesia, the Virtous: A fusion material for two differend monsters: Sanctifire and Granguignol.

1x Guiding Quem, the Virtous: Can be used sometimes, but it's very gimmicky. Mostly there just for rare occasions it can be good for doing it's effect or summoning Sanctifire.

1x Albion, the Shrouded Dragon: Just an Albaz replacement for fusion summoning from grave.

1x Gimmick Puppet Nightmare: Only there for fusion material for all monsters that need a DARK monster as a fusion material. The plan is to put him to GY and then summon him to your opponent's field during their standby phase by Sanctifire's effect to make them unable to summon other monsters.

1x Tri-Brigade Mercurier: A hand trap that can be used if you control an Albaz fusion monster (which you most likely will if you're going first)

1x Despian Tragedy: Can be used to search Aluber if foolished to the grave.

3x Ashh Blossom & Joyous Spring: I don't need to explain. Basically a combo ender for your opponent.

1x Branded Lost: Used to recycle Albaz everytime you fusion summon using him.

3x Branded Fusion: I think it's very self-explanatory.

1x Foolish Burial: As I already explained, it can come in handy for sending fusion materials to the GY.

2x Fusion Deployment: Can be used to add either Albaz or Cartesia to your hand for summoning.

2x Lightning Storm: I don't side it. It's just way too powerful and useful.

1x Monster Reborn: You can summon back a destroyed boss monster or Albaz and use it's effect to fusion summon using one of the opponent's monsters.

2x Polymerization: Can be used for fusion summoning pretty much anything, but the obvious target for it is Guardian Chimera since it cannot be summon by Branded fusion.

1x Super Polymerization: If you still have 1 card in your hand at the end of you turn, you can set Super Poly and use it to clear the opponent's board of their insane bosses.

3x Branded in Red: The second strongest fusion card you need. Returning Albaz to hand and then fusing him again is just insane, as well as doing the sam with Aluber to summon Masquarade.

3x Triple Tactics Talent: If you get handtrapped, you can take some ground back by using one of Tactics' effects.

2x Branded Opening: If you don't open with Aluber you can search him. Otherwise Opening is just a discarding material if you don't need to use it.

1x Called by the Grave: If you get Ashed, you can just negate the Ash and continue without the fear of getting Ashed again.

1x Crossout Designator: Again, can be used to negate Ash or Nibbiru or any other hand trap.

1x Branded Retribution: A negate with a GY effect to recycle one spell back to your hand from the GY.

3x Infinite Impermanence: Can be used either as a hand trap if your opponent goes first, or as a negate and a zone lock if they go second.

EXTRA:

Guardian Chimera: A very powerful boss monster for going both first and second. Can make you advantage and make the opponent disadvantage at the same time.

Albion, the Sanctifire Dragon: very good monster. You can either summon Gimmicky Puppet Nightmare to your opponent's field during their turn to lock them from summoning or summon Albaz to your field and another monster from your GY to their field and then fusion summon using Albaz's effect to fusion summon during their turn.

Borreload Furious Dragon: A mostly generic fusion target for super poly or Albaz. Can be used to detroy itself and another monster your opponent controls.

Mirrorjade, the Iceblade Dragon: The boss monster of the deck. You can use it's effect to quickly remove a good combo starter or extonder from opponent's field before thy use that monster's effect.

Lubellion the Searing Dragon: Used in the main combo to summon Mirrorjade by shuffling itself from the field and Albaz from the GY as fusion materials.

Alba-Lenatus the Abyss Dragon: Can attack multiple times to clear opponent's board or can be set to the GY by Mirrorjade's effect to add a fusion card to your hand.

Despian Quaeritis: Pretty powerful to trigger it's effect when your monster would be attacked by an opponent's boss with the higher attack to make the opponent take the damage and lose that same monster. You can also trigger it's effect EVERY turn, so you can just make all your opponent's monsters have 0 ATK nd the beat over all of them.

Granguignol the Dusk Dragon: Since most of the extra deck monsters featuring Albaz as a material have good GY effects at the end phase, you can send them there for free using Granguignol's effect. Is also a good fusion that has Cartesia as a material.

Albion the Branded Dragon: Can be used either to fusion summon using his effect or to be sent to the GY for his GY effect.

Brigrand the Glory Dragon, Titaniklad the Ash Dragon and Rindbrumm the Striking Dragon: only there for their GY effects.

Masquarade the Blazing Dragon: Very good since now the opponent has to pay 600 LP every time they activate an effect, so it can take out a very good chunk of their LP.

Predaplant Dracostapelia: Kinda generic and permanently negates a monsters effect.

SIDE:

2x Nibiru, the Primal Being: Use it aginst very combo-heavy decks WHEN THEY FINISH THE COMBO, because that's how you can make the most out of it. Otherwise they can just continue if you chained Nibiru to an effect and it then resolves.

3x Droll & Lock Bird: Makes your opponent unable to search anything, practically ending their combo right there and then.

3x Dark Ruler No More: If you go against Stardust synchro or Utopia or any other with a bunch of negates on their field, you can just negate them and continue safely.

3x Cosmic Cyclone: Very good form of backrow removal.

1x Skill Drain: Side ONLY under very dire sircumstances, as it also drains you, as well as the opponent.

3x Evely Matched: If you survive their battle phase, use ias a hand trap and remove the entirety of thier field from existance.
Watch the gates of the Dark World...
